3.2 数据处理
\subsection{Noise reduction}

Noise reduction for the song sequences was performed using the built-in \textbf{Noise Reduction} feature in Audacity. For each recording segment, a specific portion of the background noise was first selected to generate a noise profile, which was then applied to the entire segment.

The Noise Reduction parameters were set conservatively to minimize distortion of the target signal: the Noise Reduction level was set to \textbf{7 dB}.

%, Sensitivity to \textbf{6}, and Frequency Smoothing was set to \textbf{6}.

Depending on the individual noise characteristics of each recording segment, the noise reduction process was iteratively applied two to three times.

Furthermore, for song segments where the target vocalizations occurred predominantly in the high-frequency range, a \textbf{High-Pass Filter} was applied to eliminate low-frequency environmental noise. The high-pass cutoff frequency was set to \textbf{1000 Hz}.

\subsection{Loudness Normalization}

Following the noise reduction steps, the audio segments underwent a loudness normalization process to ensure consistency across the entire dataset. Specifically, the Audacity \textbf{Normalize} feature was utilized to standardize the peak amplitude of every song segment to a uniform target level of $-1.0 \text{ dB}$. This is crucial for training robust machine learning models like the Deep Audio Segmentation (DAS) system, as it prevents any single recording from having disproportionate weight due to amplitude differences.

\subsection{Syllable Annotation}
\subsubsection{Classification Methodology}
Syllable definition was based on a multi-dimensional feature analysis. The classification process utilized the following key features, observed primarily via spectrogram visualization:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Acoustic Structure / Shape (Primary Criterion):}The mode of frequency change over time was established as the most critical determinant for classification. Syllables were grouped based on their distinct geometric patterns on the spectrogram, such as:
\begin{itemize}\item \textbf{Frequency Modulated (FM) Sweeps:} Clear, rapid, continuous change in frequency (e.g., hooks, arcs, or "S" shapes).\item \textbf{Tonal Bars (Pure Tones):} Narrow-band, stable horizontal lines indicating constant or very slow frequency change.\item \textbf{Impulses / Clicks:} Short-duration, broadband vertical energy bursts.
\end{itemize}
\item \textbf{Duration (Temporal Feature):}The absolute duration of the syllable was treated as a feature dimension for subsequent clustering, but not as the single decisive factor for classification. Minor variations in duration (e.g., $10\%-20\%$ variability) between two otherwise identical syllables were accepted as natural biological variance and grouped into the same category. 
\subsubsection{annotation namaing rule}
The syllable dictionary was expanded from a basic A-U set to include alphanumeric identifiers (e.g., B1) and similarity markers (e.g., A'). Following acoustic structure analysis, similar syllables were consolidated to reduce scoring ambiguity and improve training robustness.
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\subsubsection{Resulting Syllable Inventory}
To date, the manual annotation process has yielded a inventory of 18 distinct syllable classes. This inventory will serve as the target output for the Deep Audio Segmentation (DAS) model. 对于繁殖期的音符标注一开始是比较严苛的，将结构相同但不同频率重复的音符视为不同音符，导致繁殖期的音符种类有32种，但非繁殖期音符形态变化较大，很难精准分类到繁殖期的音符种类中，因此采用了忽略频率偏移的做法，减少音符种类到18种。
