\section{Pipeline for Birds Acoustic Analysis}
The analysis pipeline is designed to process multi-channel temporal annotation data, extract song-level and syllable-level statistics, and summarize the syntactic structure of the songs in a compact, human-readable form. The workflow consists of four main stages:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Data Ingestion, Cleaning, and Node Compression}: 
    Annotation files (CSV format) from multiple recording channels are automatically scanned and loaded. For each file, the script:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Converts the \texttt{start\_seconds} and \texttt{stop\_seconds} columns to numeric values and removes rows with invalid or missing timestamps.
        \item Excludes entries labeled with the auxiliary symbol \texttt{i} and sorts all remaining syllables in ascending order of onset time to reconstruct the full song sequence.
        \item Applies a \textit{Node Compression} step on the symbolic sequence, where specific, pre-defined adjacent pairs (e.g., \texttt{R} followed by \texttt{H}, \texttt{H} followed by \texttt{R1}, or \texttt{A} followed by \texttt{H'}) are merged into a single composite unit (e.g., \texttt{(R-H)}). This reduces fragmentation of tightly coupled note pairs and yields a more compact structural representation of each song.
    \end{itemize}

    \item \textbf{Song-Level Temporal Statistics}: 
    For every individual song (each annotation file within a channel), the script computes a set of descriptive temporal features:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item \textbf{Song Duration}: The total song length is obtained as the difference between the earliest onset time and the latest offset time across all syllables.
        \item \textbf{Syllable Inventory Size}: The total number of annotated syllables and the number of unique syllable types per song are reported, characterizing both repetition and repertoire richness.
        \item \textbf{Average Syllable Duration}: The mean duration of syllables within a song is calculated from the difference between \texttt{stop\_seconds} and \texttt{start\_seconds} for each entry.
    \end{itemize}

    \item \textbf{Structural Pattern Extraction and Syllable Duration Profiling}: 
    To capture both the global structure and fine-grained timing properties of the songs, two complementary analyses are performed:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item \textbf{Compressed Structural Pattern}: The time-ordered syllable sequence of each song is first reduced using run-length encoding (grouping consecutive identical labels) and then passed through the node-compression rule set. The resulting sequence is formatted as a symbolic pattern string (e.g., \texttt{A(3)-B(2)-(R-H)(1)-C(4)}), which succinctly summarizes the arrangement and local repetition of syllable types.
        \item \textbf{Syllable Duration Statistics}: Across all processed songs and channels, individual syllable durations are pooled and grouped by label. For each syllable type, standard descriptive statistics (count, mean, standard deviation, and quantiles) of duration are computed, providing an overview of timing variability within and across note categories.
    \end{itemize}

    \item \textbf{Outputs and Downstream Use}: 
    The pipeline generates an Excel workbook that consolidates the multi-channel analysis results:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item \textbf{Song\_Summary Sheet}: Contains one row per song with the recording channel, file name, song duration, total and unique syllable counts, average syllable duration, and the compressed structural pattern string. This sheet serves as a convenient overview for comparing songs across channels and recording sessions.
        \item \textbf{Syllable\_Stats Sheet}: Stores the per-syllable-type duration statistics derived from the aggregated dataset. These summaries can be directly used for downstream visualization (e.g., histograms or violin plots of duration) and for refining syllable class definitions based on temporal consistency.
    \end{itemize}
\end{enumerate}

